{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1acf7d64-9cb1-4166-bdf1-4c27ca4f93e9","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the recommended cross-platform tool for .NET performance tracing.\n\n### Quick Steps\n\n1. **Install the tool** (one-time):\n   ```\n   dotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n   ```\n\n2. **Find your process ID**:\n   ```\n   dotnet-trace ps\n   ```\n\n3. **Collect a CPU trace** (30 seconds is usually enough):\n   ```\n   dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n   ```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternative: PerfView (deeper OS-level analysis)\nIf you need kernel-level CPU data (e.g., native code, drivers):\n```\nPerfView.exe collect -Duration:30 -CPU\n```\nDownload from [github.com/microsoft/perfview](https://github.com/microsoft/perfview). PerfView uses ETW and gives you call stacks across managed + native code.\n\n### Which to pick?\n| Scenario | Tool |\n|---|---|\n| Pure .NET managed code | `dotnet-trace` |\n| Mixed native + managed, kernel | PerfView |\n| Production, minimal overhead | `dotnet-trace` with `cpu-sampling` |\n\nFor most .NET 8 services, **`dotnet-trace` with `--profile cpu-sampling`** is the fastest path to identifying your hot methods.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7dbbf07e-b95c-438a-95ce-40c29cae99fd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question - no tools needed.","outputTokens":403},"id":"24c07442-39ac-43a9-a30d-f40c0186f544","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:45:43.447Z","parentId":"0bbbfe35-7bd0-404f-b4fe-791ee18aada9"}
